vectorData.altText: 6. A nerve contains sympathetic preganglionic fibres. What nerve might it be? Choose all that apply.
That's right!  Preganglionic sympathetic fibres pass through the ventral root, spinal nerve and white ramus communicans to enter a sympathetic chain ganglion.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Follow the fibres through the ventral root (25) and spinal nerve (26). From there, they enter a sympathetic ganglion (*) via a white ramus communicans     (30). This is the preganglionic  neuron, and its fibre the preganglionic axon     .
pre = before; the preganglionic neuron comes carries information into the sympathetic ganglion from the spinal cord
the white ramus communicans is white because its axon is coated by myelin, a lipid material that makes it white in fresh tissue.
